@Jerry
Leaving aside the fantasies, there's an obvious and well-known explanation for how that great line is always spoken in iconic closeup. Every scene is shot numerous times with different camera angles and positions: Extreme Close-Up Character 1, ECU Character 2, Over The Shoulder Char 1, OTS Char 2, Panorama Scene downstage, Pan Sc upstage, etc., etc. The film editor, often with the director, decides whether we get the line in ECU speaker or the reaction shot in OTS speaker, or the grouping of various responses in Pan, etc. Hence, by the way, the notorious 'face on the cutting room floor'.
Sure, they may know in advance which lines have real punch. I bet when Shakespeare wrote, "Tomorrow and tomorrow and tomorrow...", he didn't worry that it was too repetitive. He knew it was good stuff.

